## How to read this

- **Run min** is the minimum wall-clock over the measured rounds, not the mean.
  Contention noise is one-sided — it can only slow a run down — so the minimum
  is the best estimate of the machine's capability.
- **Dispersion** is the median absolute deviation as a percentage of the median.
  It is a verdict on the campaign, not an error bar on the result. Above roughly
  2%, the machine was too noisy for percentage-level claims and even the minimum
  should be distrusted. Being a median, it is robust: a single clobbered round
  will not show up here. Isolated spikes are found in `samples.ndjson`.
- **Compute min** is what the program timed around its own hot loop. **Startup**
  is the gap between the two clocks: container creation plus runtime
  initialisation. That gap is a result, not overhead to be subtracted.
- **CPU time** is `user + system` read from the container's cgroup. Wall-clock
  says whether it is fast; CPU time says at what price. A scheduler that
  busy-waits burns CPU without gaining a millisecond of wall.
- **`.text`** is the only binary size comparable across implementations. Total
  file size measures linking policy, not codegen. `n/a` means the backend emits
  no artifact, which is a property of the backend, not of the language.
- **Δ strict** is the checksum's distance from the strict-mode reference. In
  `strict` it is always `0` — a divergence aborts the campaign. In `fma` and
  `fast` it is the precision sold for the speed gained.

Two things this report does not say: which language is fastest (it compares
backends, and cross-language rows are confounded by construction), and how this
machine compares to one of a different ISA (absolute cross-ISA timings are
meaningless; only within-ISA ratios travel).
